import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.StringTokenizer;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String input = "923119511824|DST:9900|CNT:1|OPR:zong|ADD RIDAsMs923119511824|DST:9900|CNT:1|OPR:zong|ADD sMs923125473547|DST:9900|CNT:1|OPR:zong|ADD SahafatMedia 923138824807|DST:9900|CNT:1|OPR:zong|ADD TRIXXS 923142676343|DST:9900|CNT:1|OPR:zong|ADD BBCMEDIA\n\n 923142676343|DST:9900|CNT:1|OPR:zong|\nADD BBCLANDAN\n [2014-08-19 00:01:02,958] REC|[2014-08-19 00:01:12,799] REC|[2014-08-19 00:01:32,894] REC|[2014-08-19 00:01:43,753] REC|[2014-08-19 00:02:42,754] REC|ï»¿[2014-08-19 00:00:21,702] REC|";
        ArrayList<String> contactNumbers = new ArrayList<>();
        StringTokenizer tokenizer = new StringTokenizer(input, "|");
        
        while (tokenizer.hasMoreTokens()) {
            String token = tokenizer.nextToken();
            if (token.startsWith("SRC:")) {
                String contactNumber = token.substring(4);
                contactNumbers.add(contactNumber);
            }
        }
        
        for (String number : contactNumbers) {
            System.out.println(number);
        }
    }
}
<<<explanation>>>: 
In this code, we first define the input string which contains the values from the text file. We then create an ArrayList to store the contact numbers. We create a StringTokenizer object with the input string and the delimiter "|". 

We then iterate through the tokens using the hasMoreTokens() method. For each token, we check if it starts with "SRC:". If it does, we extract the contact number by removing the "SRC:" prefix and add it to the contactNumbers ArrayList. 

Finally, we print out the contact numbers using a for-each loop.
